{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4b944725-08d2-40b8-ad5c-d316ac161b98","content":"There's no repository-specific documentation on this topic, but here's the general guidance for macOS:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Check Apple's crash reporter** — macOS automatically captures crash logs at:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name and timestamp.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps via `ulimit`** before running:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   /path/to/your-app\n   ```\n   Core files are written to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Verify `/cores` exists and is writable:**\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Ensure SIP isn't blocking core dumps** — on modern macOS, System Integrity Protection can prevent core dumps for certain binaries. You may need to codesign your app with the `com.apple.security.get-task-allow` entitlement:\n   ```bash\n   codesign -s - --entitlements entitlements.plist --force /path/to/your-app\n   ```\n   where `entitlements.plist` contains:\n   ```xml\n   <key>com.apple.security.get-task-allow</key>\n   <true/>\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze the core dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your-app -c /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n\nThe key difference with NativeAOT (vs. CoreCLR) is that `createdump` is a CoreCLR-specific tool. NativeAOT apps are native binaries, so standard OS-level crash recovery (`/cores`, `lldb`, Diagnostic Reports) applies directly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f750dd40-e178-42f5-a85c-13b47b0b8c8b","outputTokens":461,"requestId":"C3C3:86E8:1D061DF:20A3AF8:6A07C30A"},"id":"04f5c842-5e7a-4193-8380-738cca77e407","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:06:28.488Z","parentId":"c9024122-a98c-45f0-9c11-c9fcc45c9c10"}
